I"y<p>In 1966 and 1967, New York City station WBAI hosted a series of relaxed, informal, one-on-one conversations between composers John Cage and Morton Feldman. In the first of these “Radio Happenings,” Cage explains how his experience of the radio medium changed after using it as a compositional tool. He also (around 24:00 in the recording) describes an attitude toward the music composer’s role that we will consider as a type of programming. This programmatic approach to experimental composition was expanded by other artists including Pauline Oliveros, and it will form one precdent for our artistic of deprogramming.</p>
